JOHANNESBURG Four listed insurance companies are the latest to feel the impact of South Africa's recent credit rating downgrades.Ratings agency Standard and Poor's has cut the national scale ratings of Old Mutual Life Assurance, Sanlam, Liberty, and Santam by at least a notch.S&P lowered South Africa's foreign-currency rating to junk status two weeks ago.READ: SA risks losing R150bn with more downgradingAll the insurers, however, remain above investment grade. But the agency says local economic conditions have led to increased risk in the firms balance sheets.Old Mutual says it's well capitalised and not alarmed by the downgrade. Sanlam says it does not expect the rating to have a significant impact on its solvency. eNCA